			"type":"text",
			"text":"Here's a breakdown of the key economic concepts mentioned, including **budget set**, **utility**, and the differences between **cardinal** and **ordinal utility**:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Budget Set**:\n- A **budget set** includes all the possible combinations of goods and services a person can afford based on their income and the prices of those goods.\n- **Budget Line**: This line represents the maximum combinations of two goods that a consumer can afford. Any point on or below the line is affordable.\n  \n  **Equation**: \n  \\[\n  P_1 \\cdot X_1 + P_2 \\cdot X_2 \\leq M\n  \\]\n  Where:\n  - \\( P_1 \\) and \\( P_2 \\) are the prices of goods 1 and 2.\n  - \\( X_1 \\) and \\( X_2 \\) are the quantities of goods 1 and 2.\n  - \\( M \\) is the consumer's income.\n  \n  - All combinations within the budget set lie **inside** or **on** the budget line.\n  \n---\n\n### **2. Utility**:\n- **Utility** refers to the satisfaction a consumer gets from consuming a good or service.\n  \n#### **Two Types of Utility**:\n  \n- **Cardinal Utility**: \n  - Measures satisfaction in numbers, typically using imaginary units called **utils**.\n  - For example, if pizza gives you **60 utils** and a burger gives you **40 utils**, pizza provides more satisfaction.\n  - It's a **quantitative** method.\n\n- **Ordinal Utility**:\n  - Measures satisfaction by **ranking** preferences.\n  - For instance, if you prefer pizza over a burger, you rank pizza first and the burger second, but you don’t assign numbers to the satisfaction.\n  - It’s a **qualitative** method.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Differences Between Cardinal and Ordinal Utility**:\n\n| **Cardinal Utility** | **Ordinal Utility** |\n|----------------------|---------------------|\n| Satisfaction is measured in numbers (utils). | Satisfaction is ranked based on preferences. |\n| Quantitative measurement. | Qualitative measurement. |\n| Example: Pizza gives 60 utils, Burger gives 40 utils. | Example: Pizza is preferred over a burger. |\n\n---\n\n### **4. Total and Marginal Utilities**:\n\n- **Total Utility (TU)**: \n  - The total satisfaction obtained from consuming all units of a good.\n  \n- **Marginal Utility (MU)**:\n  - The additional satisfaction gained from consuming one more unit of a good.\n  - Formula: \n  \\[\n  MU_x = \\frac{\\Delta TU}{\\Delta Q}\n  \\]\n  \n- **Relationship between Total and Marginal Utility**:\n  - **Total Utility** increases, but at a **diminishing rate**.\n  - **Marginal Utility** decreases as more units are consumed, because each additional unit gives **less satisfaction**.\n  - When **Total Utility** reaches its maximum, **Marginal Utility** becomes zero.\n\n---\n\nThis combination of budget lines and utility helps understand consumer choice and how individuals maximize satisfaction given their income and preferences.",
