			"type":"text",
			"text":"### **Consumer Equilibrium**\n\n**Consumer equilibrium** is the point at which a consumer maximizes their satisfaction (utility) given their income and the prices of goods. The consumer allocates their resources in such a way that they achieve the highest possible utility with their available budget.\n\n\n---\n\n### **1. Consumer Equilibrium for a Single Commodity**:\n- A consumer reaches equilibrium when the **marginal utility** (MU) of the commodity is equal to the **price** (P) of the commodity.\n- **Key Concept**: The consumer buys a quantity of the good where the marginal utility of the last unit consumed is equal to the price they pay for that unit.\n\n#### Example of Equilibrium for a Single Commodity:\n\n| **Units of X** | **Price (Px)** (Rs.) | **Marginal Utility** (utils) | **Marginal Utility in Rs. (MUx)** | **Difference (MUx - Px)** | **Remarks** |\n|----------------|----------------------|-----------------------------|----------------------------------|---------------------------|-------------|\n| 1              | 10                   | 20                          | 20/1 = 20                       | 10                        | MUx > Px, increase consumption |\n| 2              | 10                   | 16                          | 16/1 = 16                       | 6                         | MUx > Px, increase consumption |\n| 3              | 10                   | 10                          | 10/1 = 10                       | 0                         | Consumer Equilibrium (MUx = Px) |\n| 4              | 10                   | 4                           | 4/1 = 4                         | -6                        | MUx < Px, decrease consumption |\n| 5              | 10                   | 0                           | 0/1 = 0                         | -10                       | MUx < Px, decrease consumption |\n\n- The consumer reaches equilibrium at the 3 rd unit, where the marginal utility equals the price of Rs. 10.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Consumer Equilibrium for Two Commodities**:\nWhen consuming two goods (say, X and Y), the consumer is in equilibrium when:\n1. The **marginal utility per rupee** spent on each good is equal:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{MU_x}{P_x} = \\frac{MU_y}{P_y}\n   \\]\n   This ensures that the consumer is getting the same satisfaction from the last rupee spent on each good.\n\n2. The **slope of the indifference curve** (which represents the marginal rate of substitution, MRS) is equal to the **slope of the budget line** (the price ratio of the goods):\n   \\[\n   MRS_{xy} = \\frac{P_x}{P_y}\n   \\]\n\n#### Example of Equilibrium for Two Commodities:\n- Suppose a consumer is choosing between good X and good Y.\n- The consumer will adjust their consumption until the **marginal utility per rupee** is equal for both goods:\n  \\[\n  \\frac{MU_x}{P_x} = \\frac{MU_y}{P_y}\n  \\]\n- **Equilibrium Condition**: The consumer is satisfied when the ratio of marginal utilities to prices is equal for both goods.\n\n---\n\n### **Graphical Representation of Consumer Equilibrium**:\n- The **budget line** represents all the combinations of goods that a consumer can afford.\n- The **indifference curve** represents all combinations of goods that provide the same level of satisfaction.\n- The consumer’s equilibrium occurs at the **point where the budget line is tangent to the highest possible indifference curve**. At this point:\n  - The **slope of the indifference curve** (MRS) is equal to the **slope of the budget line**.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Points**:\n- **Single Commodity Equilibrium**: The consumer is at equilibrium when the **marginal utility** of a good equals its **price**.\n- **Two Commodities Equilibrium**: The consumer is at equilibrium when the **marginal utility per rupee** for both goods is equal and the **MRS** equals the **price ratio**.\n\nThis balance helps the consumer achieve the highest level of satisfaction with their limited resources.",
